<taxonomicName authorityName="Wuillot, in Wuillot &amp; Gillies" authorityYear="1993" box="[766,1015,1185,1211]" class="Insecta" family="Baetidae" genus="Afroptilum" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="302" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="plumosum">
<emphasis box="[766,1015,1185,1211]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="302">Afroptilum plumosum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,1112,2040]" pageId="3" pageNumber="302">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,326,1221,1248]" pageId="3" pageNumber="302">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,319,1221,1248]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="302">Subimago</emphasis>
.
</emphasis>
CUTICULAR COLORATION. Pronotum colorless. Mesonotum at most part light brownish; most sutures darker brown; colorless stripe along anterior part of medioparapsidal suture (
<figureCitation box="[1234,1309,1257,1284]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–10" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1824,1849]" captionTargetBox="[170,1417,179,1796]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[170,1417,179,1796]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–10. Potamocloeon dentatum. 1, head and thorax of male imago from Uganda; 2, its abdominal sterna and terga; 3, abdominal sterna and terga of male imago from Mali; 4, abdominal sterna and terga of male subimago from Uganda; 5, hind leg of male imago; 6, subimaginal mesonotum; 7–10, genitals: 7, holotype; 8–9, specimens from Mali; 10, specimen from Uganda." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3354879/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="302">Fig. 6</figureCitation>
). Thoracic pleura and sterna with colorless and brown areas. Wing colorless with brown microtrichia. Legs colorless, microtrichia and tarsal microlepides light brownish. Abdomen and gonostyli colorless with brownish microtrichia. Cerci colorless with setae brown.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,1112,2040]" pageId="3" pageNumber="302">TEXTURE. On legs of all pairs of both sexes, all tarsal segments covered by pointed microlepides, only small basal part of fore segment covered by microtrichia (as tibia and other leg segments).</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,1112,2040]" pageId="3" pageNumber="302">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,349,1473,1500]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="302">Imago, male</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[365,470,1473,1499]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–10" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1824,1849]" captionTargetBox="[170,1417,179,1796]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[170,1417,179,1796]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–10. Potamocloeon dentatum. 1, head and thorax of male imago from Uganda; 2, its abdominal sterna and terga; 3, abdominal sterna and terga of male imago from Mali; 4, abdominal sterna and terga of male subimago from Uganda; 5, hind leg of male imago; 6, subimaginal mesonotum; 7–10, genitals: 7, holotype; 8–9, specimens from Mali; 10, specimen from Uganda." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3354879/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="302">Figs 1–3</figureCitation>
). Head ocher with brown. Turbinate eyes brown. Thorax brown, uniformly colored dorsally, laterally and ventrally. Fore wing with one marginal intercalary per space; pterostigma with 3–5 simple, oblique, complete or/and incomplete veins (Wuillot &amp; Gillies 1993: fig. 39); bases of wings brownish, remainder colorless; veins, including costal brace, colorless. Hind wings absent. Legs of all pairs either uniformly ocher (
<figureCitation box="[160,232,1617,1644]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–10" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1824,1849]" captionTargetBox="[170,1417,179,1796]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[170,1417,179,1796]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–10. Potamocloeon dentatum. 1, head and thorax of male imago from Uganda; 2, its abdominal sterna and terga; 3, abdominal sterna and terga of male imago from Mali; 4, abdominal sterna and terga of male subimago from Uganda; 5, hind leg of male imago; 6, subimaginal mesonotum; 7–10, genitals: 7, holotype; 8–9, specimens from Mali; 10, specimen from Uganda." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3354879/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="302">Fig. 5</figureCitation>
), or middle and hind femora with faint reddish band distally. Middle and hind legs with tibia equal or slightly longer than tarsus; first tarsomere (primary 1st+2nd) much longer than others; one terminal spine on 2nd (primary 3rd) tarsomere (
<figureCitation box="[504,577,1689,1716]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–10" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1824,1849]" captionTargetBox="[170,1417,179,1796]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[170,1417,179,1796]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–10. Potamocloeon dentatum. 1, head and thorax of male imago from Uganda; 2, its abdominal sterna and terga; 3, abdominal sterna and terga of male imago from Mali; 4, abdominal sterna and terga of male subimago from Uganda; 5, hind leg of male imago; 6, subimaginal mesonotum; 7–10, genitals: 7, holotype; 8–9, specimens from Mali; 10, specimen from Uganda." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3354879/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="302">Fig. 5</figureCitation>
). Abdominal segments I–VII whitish; terga and sterna with more or less expressed unpaired gray median spot on each joining of segments; terga with or without paired diffusive pale reddish markings; lateral trachea with blackish. Segments 
<collectionCode box="[828,922,1762,1788]" pageId="3" pageNumber="302">VIII–IX</collectionCode>
with terga brown or reddish, sterna whitish, anteriorly bordered by brown; segment X brown. Unistyligers and gonostyli light ocher. Cerci uniformly whitish.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,1112,2040]" lastBlockId="4.[151,1436,153,216]" lastPageId="4" lastPageNumber="303" pageId="3" pageNumber="302">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,363,1869,1896]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="302">Male genitals</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[380,503,1869,1895]" captionStart-0="FIGURES 1–10" captionStart-1="FIGURES 11–13" captionStartId-0="2.[151,264,1824,1849]" captionStartId-1="4.[151,264,1847,1872]" captionTargetBox-0="[170,1417,179,1796]" captionTargetBox-1="[154,1421,289,1819]" captionTargetId-0="figure@2.[170,1417,179,1796]" captionTargetId-1="figure@4.[151,1436,273,1822]" captionTargetPageId-0="2" captionTargetPageId-1="4" captionText-0="FIGURES 1–10. Potamocloeon dentatum. 1, head and thorax of male imago from Uganda; 2, its abdominal sterna and terga; 3, abdominal sterna and terga of male imago from Mali; 4, abdominal sterna and terga of male subimago from Uganda; 5, hind leg of male imago; 6, subimaginal mesonotum; 7–10, genitals: 7, holotype; 8–9, specimens from Mali; 10, specimen from Uganda." captionText-1="FIGURES 11–13. 11–12, Potamocloeon dentatum: 11, genitals of subimago; 12, genitals of imago (styligeral and gonostylar muscles shown only on left side, gonoduct shown by dotted line). 13, Potamocloeon edentatum sp. n., fore wing (holotype). Abbreviations: gd – gonoduct; gs1–gs3, segments of gonostylus; m.IX-X, areas of anterior attachment of median paraproctal muscles (i.e., muscles going from sternum IX to common base of paraprocts); m.sg, median sterno-styligeral muscle." httpUri-0="https://zenodo.org/record/3354879/files/figure.png" httpUri-1="https://zenodo.org/record/3354881/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="302">Figs 7–12</figureCitation>
). Sterno-styligeral muscle very wide, proximally much wider than distance between median paraproctal muscles, distally wider than distance between unistyligers. In imago (
<figureCitation box="[1260,1378,1905,1931]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–10" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1824,1849]" captionTargetBox="[170,1417,179,1796]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[170,1417,179,1796]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–10. Potamocloeon dentatum. 1, head and thorax of male imago from Uganda; 2, its abdominal sterna and terga; 3, abdominal sterna and terga of male imago from Mali; 4, abdominal sterna and terga of male subimago from Uganda; 5, hind leg of male imago; 6, subimaginal mesonotum; 7–10, genitals: 7, holotype; 8–9, specimens from Mali; 10, specimen from Uganda." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3354879/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="302">Figs 7–10</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[1391,1422,1905,1931]" captionStart="FIGURES 11–13" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1847,1872]" captionTargetBox="[154,1421,289,1819]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[151,1436,273,1822]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 11–13. 11–12, Potamocloeon dentatum: 11, genitals of subimago; 12, genitals of imago (styligeral and gonostylar muscles shown only on left side, gonoduct shown by dotted line). 13, Potamocloeon edentatum sp. n., fore wing (holotype). Abbreviations: gd – gonoduct; gs1–gs3, segments of gonostylus; m.IX-X, areas of anterior attachment of median paraproctal muscles (i.e., muscles going from sternum IX to common base of paraprocts); m.sg, median sterno-styligeral muscle." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3354881/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="302">12</figureCitation>
), unistyliger with stretched inner-apical margin; first segment of gonostylus of composite shape, with narrowing near midlength, with inner-distal angle acute and projected distally; second segment of gonostylus nearly straight, basally narrowed; third (apical) segment of gonostylus petiolate, triangular; external part of penis semicircular; penial arms short and thick, with apices bent distally and free (not fused with penial bridge). Subimaginal gonostylus with sharply projected inner-apical angle of 1st segment (
<figureCitation box="[875,956,189,216]" captionStart="FIGURES 11–13" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1847,1872]" captionTargetBox="[154,1421,289,1819]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[151,1436,273,1822]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 11–13. 11–12, Potamocloeon dentatum: 11, genitals of subimago; 12, genitals of imago (styligeral and gonostylar muscles shown only on left side, gonoduct shown by dotted line). 13, Potamocloeon edentatum sp. n., fore wing (holotype). Abbreviations: gd – gonoduct; gs1–gs3, segments of gonostylus; m.IX-X, areas of anterior attachment of median paraproctal muscles (i.e., muscles going from sternum IX to common base of paraprocts); m.sg, median sterno-styligeral muscle." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3354881/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="303">Fig. 11</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<caption httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3354881/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="303" startId="4.[151,264,1847,1872]" targetBox="[154,1421,289,1819]" targetPageId="4">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,1847,1980]" pageId="4" pageNumber="303">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,340,1847,1872]" pageId="4" pageNumber="303">FIGURES 11–13.</emphasis>
11–12, 
<taxonomicName authorityName=": Salles, Gattolliat &amp; Sartori" authorityYear="2016" box="[423,671,1848,1872]" class="Insecta" family="Baetidae" genus="Potamocloeon" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="303" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="dentatum">
<emphasis box="[423,671,1848,1872]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="303">Potamocloeon dentatum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
: 11, genitals of subimago; 12, genitals of imago (styligeral and gonostylar muscles shown only on left side, gonoduct shown by dotted line). 13, 
<taxonomicName authority="Kluge, 2019" authorityName="Kluge" authorityYear="2019" box="[879,1139,1884,1908]" class="Insecta" family="Baetidae" genus="Potamocloeon" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="303" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="edentatum" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis box="[879,1139,1884,1908]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="303">Potamocloeon edentatum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1147,1204,1884,1907]" pageId="4" pageNumber="303" rank="species">sp. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
, fore wing (holotype). Abbreviations: gd – gonoduct; gs1–gs3, segments of gonostylus; m.IX-X, areas of anterior attachment of median paraproctal muscles (i.e., muscles going from sternum IX to common base of paraprocts); m.sg, median sterno-styligeral muscle.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1436,152,359]" box="[199,681,152,179]" pageId="5" pageNumber="304">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,152,179]" pageId="5" pageNumber="304">Dimension.</emphasis>
Fore wing length 
<quantity box="[539,677,152,179]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.0" metricValueMax="4.5" metricValueMin="3.5" pageId="5" pageNumber="304" unit="mm" value="4.0" valueMax="4.5" valueMin="3.5">3.5–4.5 mm</quantity>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1436,152,359]" pageId="5" pageNumber="304">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,332,188,215]" pageId="5" pageNumber="304">Discussion.</emphasis>
When Gillies accepted 
<taxonomicName authorityName=": Salles, Gattolliat &amp; Sartori" authorityYear="2016" box="[607,711,189,215]" class="Insecta" family="Baetidae" genus="Potamocloeon" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="304" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="dentatum">
<emphasis box="[607,711,189,215]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="304">dentatum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
[
<taxonomicName authorityName="Leach" authorityYear="1815" box="[729,810,189,215]" class="Insecta" family="Baetidae" genus="Cloeon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="304" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[729,810,189,215]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="304">Cloeon</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
] as the member of the genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Leach" authorityYear="1815" box="[1153,1234,189,215]" class="Insecta" family="Baetidae" genus="Cloeon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="304" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1153,1234,189,215]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="304">Cloeon</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, he stated that its adult differs from other species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Leach" authorityYear="1815" box="[535,616,225,251]" class="Insecta" family="Baetidae" genus="Cloeon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="304" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[535,616,225,251]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="304">Cloeon</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in longer vein MA2, which reaches «up to or almost to the cross-vein between MA1 and 
<collectionCode box="[338,384,261,287]" country="0" name="Mohonk Preserve, Inc." pageId="5" pageNumber="304">MP</collectionCode>
1» (
<bibRefCitation author="Gillies, M. T." box="[421,619,261,287]" pageId="5" pageNumber="304" pagination="135 - 156" refId="ref6282" refString="Gillies, M. T. (1980) An introduction to the study of Cloeon Leach (Baetidae, Ephemeroptera) in West Africa. Bulletin de l'Institut Francais d'Afrique Noire (Series A), 42 (1), 135 - 156." type="journal article" year="1980">Gillies 1980: 148</bibRefCitation>
, fig. 6; 
<bibRefCitation author="Gillies, M. T." box="[705,889,260,287]" pageId="5" pageNumber="304" pagination="49 - 59" refId="ref6380" refString="Gillies, M. T. (1988) Descriptions of the nymphs of some Afrotropical Baetidae (Ephemeroptera). I. Cloeon Leach and Rhithrocloeon Gillies. Aquatic Insects, 10 (1), 49 - 59. https: // doi. org / 10.1080 / 01650428809361310" type="journal article" year="1988">Gillies 1988: 52</bibRefCitation>
). Among two specimens collected by me in Jinja (the 
<typeStatus box="[203,251,297,323]" pageId="5" pageNumber="304">type</typeStatus>
locality), one (male subimago) has such long MA2, while another (male imago) has MA2 much shorter, far not reaching this cross vein. The same variability is found among male imagines and subimagines from 
<collectingCountry box="[1353,1409,333,359]" name="Serbia" pageId="5" pageNumber="304">Mali</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
